(noun.person)

{ imaginary_being, imaginary_creature, noun.cognition:imagination1,@ (a creature of the imagination; a person that exists only in legends or myths or fiction) }
{ hypothetical_creature, imaginary_being,@ (a creature that has not been observed but is hypothesized to exist) }
{ extraterrestrial_being, [ extraterrestrial, adj.pert:extraterrestrial,+ ] [ alien2, adj.all:foreign1^alien,+ ] hypothetical_creature,@ (a form of life assumed to exist outside the Earth or its atmosphere) }
{ mythical_being, imaginary_being,@ (an imaginary being of myth or fable) }
{ [ Augeas, adj.all:dirty1^Augean,+ ] mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the mythical Greek king who for 30 years did not clean his stables which contained his vast herd of cattle) }
{ Alcyone, Halcyon, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a woman who was turned into a kingfisher) }
{ Arjuna, mythical_being,@i noun.cognition:Hinduism,;c noun.group:mythology,;c ((Hindu mythology) the warrior prince in the Bhagavad-Gita to whom Krishna explains the nature of being and of God and how humans can come to know God) }
{ legendary_creature, mythical_monster,@ (a monster that is unverifiable but popularly accepted as possibly factual) }
{ abominable_snowman, yeti, legendary_creature,@ (a large hairy humanoid creature said to live in the Himalayas) }
{ Bigfoot, Sasquatch, legendary_creature,@i (large hairy humanoid creature said to live in wilderness areas of the United States and Canada) }
{ Demogorgon, deity,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a mysterious and terrifying deity of the underworld) }
{ doppelganger, legendary_creature,@ (a ghostly double of a living person that haunts its living counterpart) }
{ Loch_Ness_monster, Nessie, legendary_creature,@i noun.object:Loch_Ness,#p (a large aquatic animal supposed to resemble a serpent or plesiosaur of Loch Ness in Scotland) }
{ sea_serpent, legendary_creature,@ (huge creature of the sea resembling a snake or dragon) }
{ bogeyman, bugbear, bugaboo, boogeyman, booger, monster2,@ (an imaginary monster used to frighten children) }
{ [ Death, verb.change:die,+ verb.perception:die,+ ] imaginary_being,@i (the personification of death; "Death walked the streets of the plague-bound city") }
{ [ Gargantua, adj.all:large^gargantuan,+ ] imaginary_being,@i (a voracious giant in Francois Rabelais' book of the same name) }
{ Grim_Reaper, Reaper1, Death,@i (Death personified as an old man or a skeleton with a scythe) }
{ [ giant2, adj.all:large^giant,+ adj.all:large^gigantic1,+ ] imaginary_being,@ (an imaginary figure of superhuman size and strength; appears in folklore and fairy tales) }
{ hobbit, imaginary_being,@ (an imaginary being similar to a person but smaller and with hairy feet; invented by J.R.R. Tolkien) }
{ Maxwell's_demon, imaginary_being,@i (an imaginary creature that controls a small hole in a partition that divides a chamber filled with gas into two parts and allows fast molecules to move in one direction and slow molecules to move in the other direction through the hole; this would result in one part of the container becoming warmer and the other cooler, thus decreasing entropy and violating the second law of thermodynamics) }
{ mermaid, imaginary_being,@ (half woman and half fish; lives in the sea) }
{ merman, imaginary_being,@ (half man and half fish; lives in the sea) }
{ Martian, imaginary_being,@i (imaginary people who live on the planet Mars) }
{ Argus, giant2,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a giant with 100 eyes; was guardian of the heifer Io and was slain by Hermes) }
{ Cadmus, imaginary_being,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the brother of Europa and traditional founder of Thebes in Boeotia) }
{ Calypso, sea_nymph,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the sea nymph who detained Odysseus for seven years) }
{ sea_nymph, water_nymph,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a water nymph who was the daughter of Oceanus or Nereus) }
{ [ Cyclops, adj.pert:cyclopean,+ ] giant2,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of a group of giants having a single eye in the middle of their forehead) }
{ giantess, giant2,@ (a female giant) }
{ ogre, giant2,@ noun.cognition:folklore,;c ((folklore) a giant who likes to eat human beings) }
{ ogress, ogre,@ ((folklore) a female ogre) }
{ Humpty_Dumpty, imaginary_being,@i (an egg-shaped character in a nursery rhyme who fell off a wall and could not be put back together again (late 17th century)) }
{ Jack_Frost, imaginary_being,@i (a personification of frost or winter weather) }
{ Mammon, imaginary_being,@i noun.communication:New_Testament,;c ((New Testament) a personification of wealth and avarice as an evil spirit; "ye cannot serve God and Mammon") }
{ Scylla, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a sea nymph transformed into a sea monster who lived on one side of a narrow strait; drowned and devoured sailors who tried to escape Charybdis (a whirlpool) on the other side of the strait) }
{ Stentor1, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c (the mythical Greek warrior with an unusually loud voice who died after losing a shouting contest with Hermes) }
{ monster2, imaginary_being,@ (an imaginary creature usually having various human and animal parts) }
{ mythical_monster, mythical_creature, monster2,@ mythical_being,@ (a monster renowned in folklore and myth) }
{ amphisbaena, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:classical_mythology,;c ((classical mythology) a serpent with a head at each end of its body) }
{ basilisk, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:classical_mythology,;c ((classical mythology) a serpent (or lizard or dragon) able to kill with its breath or glance) }
{ centaur, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:classical_mythology,;c ((classical mythology) a mythical being that is half man and half horse) }
{ Cerberus, hellhound1, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the three-headed dog guarding the entrance to Hades; son of Typhon) }
{ Charon, ferryman,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the ferryman who brought the souls of the dead across the river Styx or the river Acheron to Hades) }
{ [ Chimera, adj.pert:chimeral,+ adj.pert:chimerical,+ ] Chimaera, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) fire-breathing female monster with a lion's head and a goat's body and a serpent's tail; daughter of Typhon) }
{ Chiron, centaur,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the learned centaur who tutored Achilles, Asclepius, Hercules, Jason, and other heroes) }
{ Circe, sorceress,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a sorceress who detained Odysseus on her island and turned his men into swine) }
{ cockatrice, mythical_monster,@ (monster hatched by a reptile from a cock's egg; able to kill with a glance) }
{ Dardanus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) founder of Troy) }
{ dragon2, firedrake, mythical_monster,@ (a creature of Teutonic mythology; usually represented as breathing fire and having a reptilian body and sometimes wings) }
{ Fafnir, dragon2,@i noun.group:Norse_mythology,;c ((Norse mythology) the Norse dragon that guarded a treasure and was slain by Sigurd) }
{ Ganymede, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a Trojan boy who was so beautiful that Zeus carried him away to serve as cupbearer to the gods) }
{ Geryon, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a mythical monster with three heads that was slain by Hercules) }
{ Gorgon, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) any of three winged sister monsters and the mortal Medusa who had live snakes for hair; a glance at Medusa turned the beholder to stone) }
{ Grace, Greek_deity,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of three sisters who were the givers of beauty and charm; a favorite subject for sculptors) }
{ Aglaia, Grace,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of the three Graces) }
{ Euphrosyne, Grace,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of the three Graces) }
{ Thalia1, Grace,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of the three Graces) }
{ gryphon, griffin, griffon, mythical_monster,@ (winged monster with the head of an eagle and the body of a lion) }
{ Harpy1, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) vicious winged monster; often depicted as a bird with the head of a woman) }
{ Hydra, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) monster with nine heads; when struck off each head was replaced by two new ones; "Hydra was slain by Hercules") }
{ Hyperborean, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of a people that the ancient Greeks believed lived in a warm and sunny land north of the source of the north wind) }
{ Hypnos, deity,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the Greek god of sleep; the son of Nyx) }
{ leviathan2, mythical_monster,@ (monstrous sea creature symbolizing evil in the Old Testament) }
{ Niobe, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the daughter of Tantalus whose boasting about her children provoked Apollo and Artemis to slay them all; Niobe was turned to stone while bewailing her loss) }
{ Perseus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the son of Zeus who slew Medusa (with the help of Athena and Hermes) and rescued Andromeda from a sea monster) }
{ Andromeda, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) an Ethiopian princess and daughter of Cassiopeia; she was fastened to a rock and exposed to a sea monster that was sent by Poseidon, but she was rescued by Perseus and became his wife) }
{ Cepheus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) king of Ethiopia and husband of Cassiopeia) }
{ Cassiopeia, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the wife of Cepheus and mother of Andromeda) }
{ Medusa, Gorgon,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a woman transformed into a Gorgon by Athena; she was slain by Perseus) }
{ Stheno, Gorgon,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of the three Gorgons) }
{ Euryale, Gorgon,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) one of the three Gorgons) }
{ manticore, mantichora, manticora, mantiger, mythical_monster,@ (a mythical monster having the head of man (with horns) and the body of a lion and the tail of a scorpion) }
{ Midas, mythical_being,@i noun.location:Greece,;r noun.communication:legend1,;c ((Greek legend) the greedy king of Phrygia who Dionysus gave the power to turn everything he touched into gold) }
{ [ Sisyphus, adj.all:effortful^sisyphean,+ adj.pert:sisyphean,+ ] mythical_being,@i noun.location:Greece,;r noun.communication:legend1,;c ((Greek legend) a king in ancient Greece who offended Zeus and whose punishment was to roll a huge boulder to the top of a steep hill; each time the boulder neared the top it rolled back down and Sisyphus was forced to start again) }
{ Minotaur, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a mythical monster with the head of a bull and the body of a man; slain by Theseus) }
{ Morpheus, deity,@i Ovid,;c (the Roman god of sleep and dreams) }
{ Narcissus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a beautiful young man who fell in love with his own reflection) }
{ Nemean_lion, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) an enormous lion strangled by Hercules as the first of his 12 labors) }
{ Nibelung, dwarf1,@ Teuton,;c noun.group:mythology,;c ((German mythology) any of the group of dwarfs who possessed a treasure hoard that was stolen by Siegfried) }
{ Nibelung1, mythical_being,@i Teuton,;c noun.group:mythology,;c ((German mythology) a companion or follower of Siegfried) }
{ Bellerophon, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a mythical hero of Corinth who performed miracles on the winged horse Pegasus (especially killing the monster Chimera)) }
{ Paris, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the prince of Troy who abducted Helen from her husband Menelaus and provoked the Trojan War) }
{ Patroclus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a friend of Achilles who was killed in the Trojan War; his death led Achilles to return to the fight after his quarrel with Agamemnon) }
{ Pegasus, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) the immortal winged horse that sprang from the blood of the slain Medusa; was tamed by Bellerophon with the help of a bridle given him by Athena; as the flying horse of the Muses it is a symbol of highflying imagination) }
{ phoenix, mythical_being,@ (a legendary Arabian bird said to periodically burn itself to death and emerge from the ashes as a new phoenix; according to most versions only one phoenix lived at a time and it renewed itself every 500 years) }
{ Python, mythical_monster,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) dragon killed by Apollo at Delphi) }
{ roc, mythical_monster,@ (mythical bird of prey having enormous size and strength) }
{ salamander, mythical_monster,@ (reptilian creature supposed to live in fire) }
{ Sarpedon, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a son of Zeus who became king of Lycia; fought on behalf of the Trojans in the Trojan War and was killed by Patroclus) }
{ Siegfried, mythical_being,@i Teuton,;c noun.group:mythology,;c ((German mythology) mythical German warrior hero of the Nibelungenlied who takes possession of the accursed treasure of the Nibelungs by slaying the dragon that guards it and awakens Brynhild and is eventually killed; Sigurd is the Norse counterpart) }
{ Sigurd, mythical_being,@i noun.group:Norse_mythology,;c ((Norse mythology) mythical Norse warrior hero who gains an accursed hoard of gold and was killed by Brynhild; Siegfried is the German counterpart) }
{ Sphinx, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a riddling winged monster with a woman's head and breast on a lion's body; daughter of Typhon) }
{ troll, mythical_monster,@ noun.cognition:folklore,;c noun.location:Scandinavia,;r ((Scandanavian folklore) a supernatural creature (either a dwarf or a giant) that is supposed to live in caves or in the mountains) }
{ Typhoeus, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) son of Gaea and Tartarus who created the whirlwinds; had a terrifying voice and 100 dragon heads that spurted fire) }
{ Typhon, mythical_monster,@ noun.group:Greek_mythology,;c ((Greek mythology) a monster with a hundred heads who breathed out flames; son of Typhoeus and father of Cerberus and the Chimera and the Sphinx) }
{ werewolf, wolfman1, lycanthrope, loup-garou, mythical_monster,@ (a monster able to change appearance from human to wolf and back again) }
{ [ witch1, verb.communication:witch,+ ] imaginary_being,@ noun.group:coven,#m (a being (usually female) imagined to have special powers derived from the devil) }
{ wyvern, wivern, dragon2,@ (a fire-breathing dragon used in medieval heraldry; had the head of a dragon and the tail of a snake and a body with wings and two legs) }

{ nature, noun.Tops:causal_agent,@ (a causal agent creating and controlling things in the universe; "the laws of nature"; "nature has seen to it that men are stronger than women") }
{ [ supernatural, adj.all:supernatural,+ ] [ occult, adj.all:esoteric^occult,+ ] noun.Tops:causal_agent,@ (supernatural forces and events and beings collectively; "She doesn't believe in the supernatural") }
{ spiritual_being, supernatural_being, noun.cognition:belief,@ supernatural,#m (an incorporeal being believed to have powers to affect the course of human events) }
{ theurgy, noun.Tops:causal_agent,@ supernatural,#p (the effect of supernatural or divine intervention in human affairs) }
{ first_cause, prime_mover, primum_mobile, noun.Tops:causal_agent,@ (an agent that is the cause of all things but does not itself have a cause; "God is the first cause") }
{ control, spirit,@ (a spiritual agency that is assumed to assist the medium during a seance) }
{ destiny, [ fate, verb.communication:fate,+ ] noun.Tops:causal_agent,@ supernatural,#p (the ultimate agency regarded as predetermining the course of events (often personified as a woman); "we are helpless in the face of destiny") }
{ spiritual_leader, leader,@ (a leader in religious or sacred affairs) }
{ [ deity, verb.cognition:deify,+ ] [ divinity, adj.all:heavenly^divine2,+ ] god1, immortal, supernatural_being,@ noun.group:pantheon,#m (any supernatural being worshipped as controlling some part of the world or some aspect of life or who is the personification of a force) }
{ daemon1, demigod, deity,@ (a person who is part mortal and part god) }
{ Fury, Eumenides, Erinyes, mythical_monster,@i noun.group:classical_mythology,;c ((classical mythology) the hideous snake-haired monsters (usually three in number) who pursued unpunished criminals) }
{ Alecto, Fury,@ (one of the three Furies) }
{ Megaera, Fury,@ (one of the three Furies) }
{ Tisiphone, Fury,@ (one of the three Furies) }
{ sea_god, deity,@ (a deity that personifies the sea and is usually believed to live in or to control the sea) }
{ sun_god, deity,@ (a god that personifies the sun or is otherwise associated with the sun) }

{ Celtic_deity, deity,@ (a deity worshipped by the Celts) }
{ Amaethon, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (the farmer god; ancient god of agriculture) }
{ Ana, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r noun.time:antiquity,;c (mother of the ancient Irish gods; sometimes identified with Danu) }
{ Angus_Og, Aengus, Oengus, Angus, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic god of love and beauty; patron deity of young men and women) }
{ Arawn, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic deity who was the lord of Annwfn (the other world or the land of fairies)) }
{ Arianrhod, Arianrod, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic goddess famous for her beauty; mother of Dylan) }
{ Boann, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic goddess; mother of Angus Og) }
{ Brigit, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic goddess of fire and fertility and agriculture and household arts and wisdom; later associated with Saint Bridget) }
{ Dagda, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (chief Celtic god of the Tuatha De Danann; father of Angus Og and Brigit) }
{ Danu, Dana, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic goddess who was the mother of the Tuatha De Danann; identified with the Welsh Don) }
{ Don, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic goddess; mother of Gwydion and Arianrhod; corresponds to Irish Danu) }
{ Dylan1, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic god of the waves; son of Arianrhod) }
{ Epona, Celtic_deity,@i noun.group:Roman_mythology,;c ((possibly Roman mythology) Celtic goddess of horses and mules and asses) }
{ Fomor, Fomorian, Celtic_deity,@ noun.location:Ireland,;r (one of a group of Celtic sea demons sometimes associated with the hostile power of nature) }
{ Gwydion, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic sky god; a magician; giver of arts and civilization) }
{ Gwyn, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic underworld god) }
{ Lir, Ler, Celtic_deity,@ noun.location:Ireland,;r (the sea personified; father of Manannan; corresponds to Welsh Llyr) }
{ Llew_Llaw_Gyffes, Celtic_deity,@ noun.location:Wales,;r (son of Gwydion and Arianrhod; supported by magic of Gwydion; cursed by Arianrhod) }
{ LLud, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (a Celtic warrior god) }
{ Llyr, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic deity who was the father of Manawydan; corresponds to Irish Lir) }
{ Lug, Lugh, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r noun.time:antiquity,;c (ancient Celtic god) }
{ Manannan, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic god of the sea; son of Ler) }
{ Manawydan, Manawyddan, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Wales,;r (Celtic sea god; son of Llyr) }
{ Morrigan, Morrigu, Celtic_deity,@i noun.location:Ireland,;r (Celtic war goddess) }
{ Tuatha_De_Danann, Tuatha_De, Celtic_deity,@ noun.location:Ireland,;r (group of Celtic gods or demigods; ruled Ireland in the Golden Age) }
{ Egyptian_deity, deity,@ noun.time:antiquity,;c (a deity worshipped by the ancient Egyptians) }
{ Amen, Amon, Amun, Egyptian_deity,@i (a primeval Egyptian personification of air and breath; worshipped especially at Thebes) }
{ Amen-Ra, Amon-Ra, Amun_Ra, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian sun god; supreme god of the universe in whom Amen and Ra were merged; principal deity during Theban supremacy) }
{ Anubis, Anpu, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian god of tombs and ruler of the underworld; usually depicted as a man with the head of a jackal) }
{ Aten, Aton, Egyptian_deity,@i (the sun (or solar disc) which was the deity of a monotheistic cult under the Pharaoh Akhenaten) }
{ Bast, Egyptian_deity,@i (cat- or lion-headed Egyptian goddess; represents life-giving power of the sun) }
{ Geb, Keb, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian god of the earth; father of Osiris and Isis) }
{ Horus, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian solar god with the head of a falcon; the son of Osiris and Isis) }
{ Isis, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian goddess of fertility; daughter of Geb; sister and wife of Osiris) }
{ Khepera, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian god of the morning sun; creator) }
{ Min, Egyptian_deity,@i (an Egyptian god of procreation) }
{ Nephthys, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian goddess associated with ritual of the dead; sister of Geb and Nut; wife of Set) }
{ Nut, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian goddess of the sky) }
{ Osiris, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian god of the underworld and judge of the dead; husband and brother of Isis; father of Horus) }
{ Ptah, Egyptian_deity,@i (a major Egyptian god; shaper of the world; father of gods and men; worshipped especially at Memphis) }
{ Ra, Re, Egyptian_deity,@i noun.time:antiquity,;c (ancient Egyptian sun god with the head of a hawk; a universal creator; he merged with the god Amen as Amen-Ra to become the king of the gods) }
{ Sekhet, Eye_of_Ra, Egyptian_deity,@i (a lion-headed Egyptian goddess; typifies life-destroying power of the sun) }
{ Set, Seth1, Egyptian_deity,@i (evil Egyptian god with the head of a beast that has high square ears and a long snout; brother and murderer of Osiris) }
{ Thoth, Egyptian_deity,@i (Egyptian Moon deity with the head of an ibis; god of wisdom and learning and the arts; scribe of the gods) }

{ Semitic_deity, deity,@ noun.time:antiquity,;c (a deity worshipped by the ancient Semites) }
{ Adad, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (Babylonian god of storms and wind) }
{ Adapa, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (a Babylonian demigod or first man (sometimes identified with Adam)) }
{ Anshar, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (the Babylonian father of the gods; identified with Assyrian Ashur; in Sumerian the name signifies `the totality of the upper world') }
{ Antum, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (Babylonian consort of Anu) }
{ Anu, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (Babylonian god of the sky; one of the supreme triad including Bel and Ea) }
{ Anunnaki, Enuki, Semitic_deity,@ noun.location:Babylon,;r (any of a group of powerful Babylonian earth spirits or genii; servitors of the gods) }
{ Apsu, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Mesopotamia,;r (father of the gods and consort of Tiamat) }
{ Aruru, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Mesopotamia,;r (mother and earth goddess in Gilgamish epic; identified with Sumerian Ki and Ninkhursag) }
{ Ashur, Ashir, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Assyria,;r (chief god of the Assyrians; god of military prowess and empire; identified with Babylonian Anshar) }
{ Astarte, Ashtoreth, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Phoenicia,;r (an ancient Phoenician goddess of love and fertility; the Phoenician counterpart to Ishtar) }
{ Ishtar, Mylitta, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r noun.location:Assyria,;r (Babylonian and Assyrian goddess of love and fertility and war; counterpart to the Phoenician Astarte) }
{ Baal, Semitic_deity,@i (any of numerous local fertility and nature deities worshipped by ancient Semitic peoples; the Hebrews considered Baal a false god) }
{ Bel, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r (Babylonian god of the earth; one of the supreme triad including Anu and Ea; earlier identified with En-lil) }
{ Dagon, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Phoenicia,;r noun.location:Philistia,;r (god of agriculture and the earth; national god of Philistines) }
{ Dagan, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Mesopotamia,;r (god of agriculture and earth; counterpart of Phoenician Dagon) }
{ Damkina, Damgalnunna, Semitic_deity,@i noun.location:Babylon,;r ((Babylonian) earth goddess; consort of Ea and mother of Marduk) }
{ Dumuzi, Tammuz, Semitic_deity,@i (Sumerian and Babylonian god of pastures and vegetation; consort of Inanna) }
